JK Rowling's new book, ‘Harry Potter and the Cursed Child’, has become the best-selling in Great Britain, The Daily Mail reports.
The novel pushed ahead of William Shakespeare's play, ‘Romeo and Juliet’, in terms of popularity.
According to the publication, 847,9 thousand copies were sold in the first week following the release of the eighth instalment of the saga about the wizard.
The book, ‘Harry Potter and the Cursed Child’, has brought in 8.76 million pound sterling.
Thus, Shakespeare's tragedy wound up in second place: since 1998, almost 127,7 thousand copies have been sold by the publisher, Penguin Classics.
The eighth instalment of the saga of the wizard from Hogwarts, ‘Harry Potter and the Cursed Child’, was released on 31 July.
The play takes place 19 years after the events described in the book, ‘Harry Potter and the Deathly Hallows’.
On the same day, the premiere of the play was staged at the Palace Theatre in London.
In Russia, the English version of the novel hit the shelves of Moscow House of Books, the only official retailer of the novel, on 5 August.
All the copies were sold out within a day.
The new instalment of the saga will be released in Russian by the end of 2016.
